{"title_page": "Andrzej Strejlau", "text_new": "{{short description|Polish footballer and handball player}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Andrzej Strejlau\n| image = Andrzej Strejlau (2018).jpg\n| caption = Andrzej Strejlau, 2018\n| fullname = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1940|02|19|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Warszawa]], [[Poland]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place =\n| height = \n| currentclub = \n| position = Manager\n| years1 = \n| clubs1 = \n| caps1 = | goals1 = \n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1 = \n| nationalcaps1 = | nationalgoals1 = \n| manageryears1 = 1974\u20131975\n| managerclubs1 = [[Poland national under-21 football team|Poland U-21]]\n| manageryears2 = 1975\u20131979\n| managerclubs2 = [[Legia Warszawa]]\n| manageryears3 = 1979\u20131980\n| managerclubs3 = [[Zag\u0142\u0119bie Sosnowiec]]\n| manageryears4 = 1982\u20131983\n| managerclubs4 = [[Knattspyrnuf\u00e9lagi\u00f0 Fram|Fram]]\n| manageryears5 = 1984\u20131986\n| managerclubs5 = [[Larissa F.C.|Larissa]]\n| manageryears6 = 1987\u20131989\n| managerclubs6 = [[Legia Warszawa]]\n| manageryears7 = 1989\u20131993\n| managerclubs7 = [[Poland national football team|Poland]]\n| manageryears8 = 1995\u20131996\n| managerclubs8 = [[Zag\u0142\u0119bie Lubin]]\n| manageryears9 = 1997\u20131998\n| managerclubs9 = [[Shanghai Shenhua F.C.|Shanghai Shenhua]]\n}}\n\n'''Andrzej Strejlau''' (born February 19, 1940) is a retired [[Poland|Polish]] [[football (soccer)|football]] and [[handball]] player.\n\nIn 1989-1993 he was a coach of [[Poland national football team]]. He also coached many teams from different parts of the world ([[China]], [[Iceland]], [[Greece]])\n\nHe has coached [[Poland national under-21 football team|Poland U-21]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://footballdatabase.eu/football.joueurs.andrzej.strejlau.90201.en.html |title=Football : Andrzej Strejlau |publisher=Footballdatabase.eu |date= |accessdate=2012-07-06}}</ref> [[Legia Warszawa]],<ref>[http://www.legialive.pl/historia/slawy.php?pilkarz=strejlau] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100107092106/http://www.legialive.pl/historia/slawy.php?pilkarz=strejlau |date=January 7, 2010 }}</ref> [[Zag\u0142\u0119bie Sosnowiec]], [[Knattspyrnuf\u00e9lagi\u00f0 Fram]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kaninka.net/stefan/2007/12/19/%C3%BEjalfaratal-fram/ |title=Um tilgangsleysi allra hluta \u00bb Blog Archive \u00bb \u00dej\u00e1lfaratal Fram |publisher=Kaninka.net |date=2007-12-19 |accessdate=2012-07-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080423222602/http://kaninka.net/stefan/2007/12/19/%C3%BEjalfaratal-fram/ |archivedate=2008-04-23 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mbl.is/mm/gagnasafn/grein.html?grein_id=371987 |title=Vilhj\u00e1lmur B. Hj\u00f6rleifsson |publisher=Mbl.is |date= |accessdate=2012-07-06}}</ref> [[Larissa F.C.|Larissa]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polishsoca.com/newswire/poles-abroad/2063-still-trouble-for-ebi-even-in-kavala |title=Still trouble for Ebi, even in Kavala? - PSN |publisher=Polishsoca.com |date=2010-01-15 |accessdate=2012-07-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120219113120/http://www.polishsoca.com/newswire/poles-abroad/2063-still-trouble-for-ebi-even-in-kavala |archivedate=2012-02-19 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesg/grk85.html |title=Greece 1984/85 |publisher=Rsssf.com |date= |accessdate=2012-07-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesg/grk86.html |title=Greece 1985/86 |publisher=Rsssf.com |date= |accessdate=2012-07-06}}</ref> and [[Zag\u0142\u0119bie Lubin]].\n\nHe was later a member of the suspended board of [[PZPN]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Legia Warszawa managers}}\n{{AEL F.C. managers}}\n{{Poland national football team managers}}\n{{Shanghai Shenhua F.C. managers}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Strejlau, Andrzej}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Polish footballers]]\n[[Category:Polish football managers]]\n[[Category:Poland national football team managers]]\n[[Category:Legia Warsaw managers]]\n[[Category:Zag\u0142\u0119bie Sosnowiec managers]]\n[[Category:Knattspyrnuf\u00e9lagi\u00f0 Fram managers]]\n[[Category:AE Larissa FC managers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Warsaw]]\n[[Category:Polish male handball players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in China]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Iceland]]\n[[Category:Hutnik Warszawa managers]]\n[[Category:Association footballers not categorized by position]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Polish footballer and handball player}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Andrzej Strejlau\n| image = Andrzej Strejlau (2018).jpg\n| caption = Andrzej Strejlau, 2018\n| fullname = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1940|02|19|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Warszawa]], [[Poland]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place =\n| height = \n| currentclub = \n| position = Manager\n| years1 = \n| clubs1 = \n| caps1 = | goals1 = \n| nationalyears1 = \n| nationalteam1 = \n| nationalcaps1 = | nationalgoals1 = \n| manageryears1 = 1974\u20131975\n| managerclubs1 = [[Poland national under-21 football team|Poland U-21]]\n| manageryears2 = 1975\u20131979\n| managerclubs2 = [[Legia Warszawa]]\n| manageryears3 = 1979\u20131980\n| managerclubs3 = [[Zag\u0142\u0119bie Sosnowiec]]\n| manageryears4 = 1982\u20131983\n| managerclubs4 = [[Knattspyrnuf\u00e9lagi\u00f0 Fram|Fram]]\n| manageryears5 = 1984\u20131986\n| managerclubs5 = [[Larissa F.C.|Larissa]]\n| manageryears6 = 1987\u20131989\n| managerclubs6 = [[Legia Warszawa]]\n| manageryears7 = 1989\u20131993\n| managerclubs7 = [[Poland national football team|Poland]]\n| manageryears8 = 1995\u20131996\n| managerclubs8 = [[Zag\u0142\u0119bie Lubin]]\n| manageryears9 = 1997\u20131998\n| managerclubs9 = [[Shanghai Shenhua F.C.|Shanghai Shenhua]]\n}}\n\n'''Andrzej Strejlau''' (born February 19, 1940) is a retired [[Poland|Polish]] [[football (soccer)|football]] and [[handball]] player.\n\nIn 1989-1993 he was a coach of [[Poland national football team]]. He also coached many teams from different parts of the world ([[China]], [[Iceland]], [[Greece]])\n\nHe has coached [[Poland national under-21 football team|Poland U-21]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://footballdatabase.eu/football.joueurs.andrzej.strejlau.90201.en.html |title=Football : Andrzej Strejlau |publisher=Footballdatabase.eu |date= |accessdate=2012-07-06}}</ref> [[Legia Warszawa]],<ref>[http://www.legialive.pl/historia/slawy.php?pilkarz=strejlau] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100107092106/http://www.legialive.pl/historia/slawy.php?pilkarz=strejlau |date=January 7, 2010 }}</ref> [[Zag\u0142\u0119bie Sosnowiec]], [[Knattspyrnuf\u00e9lagi\u00f0 Fram]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kaninka.net/stefan/2007/12/19/%C3%BEjalfaratal-fram/ |title=Um tilgangsleysi allra hluta \u00bb Blog Archive \u00bb \u00dej\u00e1lfaratal Fram |publisher=Kaninka.net |date=2007-12-19 |accessdate=2012-07-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080423222602/http://kaninka.net/stefan/2007/12/19/%C3%BEjalfaratal-fram/ |archivedate=2008-04-23 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mbl.is/mm/gagnasafn/grein.html?grein_id=371987 |title=Vilhj\u00e1lmur B. Hj\u00f6rleifsson |publisher=Mbl.is |date= |accessdate=2012-07-06}}</ref> [[Larissa F.C.|Larissa]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polishsoca.com/newswire/poles-abroad/2063-still-trouble-for-ebi-even-in-kavala |title=Still trouble for Ebi, even in Kavala? - PSN |publisher=Polishsoca.com |date=2010-01-15 |accessdate=2012-07-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120219113120/http://www.polishsoca.com/newswire/poles-abroad/2063-still-trouble-for-ebi-even-in-kavala |archivedate=2012-02-19 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesg/grk85.html |title=Greece 1984/85 |publisher=Rsssf.com |date= |accessdate=2012-07-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesg/grk86.html |title=Greece 1985/86 |publisher=Rsssf.com |date= |accessdate=2012-07-06}}</ref> and [[Zag\u0142\u0119bie Lubin]].\n\nHe was later a member of the suspended board of [[PZPN]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Legia Warszawa managers}}\n{{AEL F.C. managers}}\n{{Poland national football team managers}}\n{{Shanghai Shenhua F.C. managers}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Strejlau, Andrzej}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:Polish footballers]]\n[[Category:Polish football managers]]\n[[Category:Poland national football team managers]]\n[[Category:Legia Warsaw managers]]\n[[Category:Zag\u0142\u0119bie Sosnowiec managers]]\n[[Category:Knattspyrnuf\u00e9lagi\u00f0 Fram managers]]\n[[Category:AE Larissa FC managers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Warsaw]]\n[[Category:Polish male handball players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in China]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Iceland]]\n[[Category:Hutnik Warszawa managers]]\n[[Category:Association footballers not categorized by position]]\n", "name_user": "Severo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:AddingCategory:Footballers from Warsaw", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrzej_Strejlau"}
{"title_page": "Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name           = Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica\n|image          = Flickr - europeanpeoplesparty - EPP Congress Rome 2006 (68)-Cropped.jpg\n|honorific_prefix = [[Doctor of law|Dr. iur.]]\n|caption        = Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica during the 2006 European People's Party Congress in Rome, Italy\n|office         = [[List of Prime Ministers of Serbia|8th]] [[Prime Minister of Serbia]]\n|president      = [[Dragan Mar\u0161i\u0107anin]] {{small|(acting)}}<br />[[Vojislav Mihailovi\u0107]] {{small|(acting)}}<br />[[Predrag Markovi\u0107]] {{small|(acting)}}<br />[[Boris Tadi\u0107]]\n|deputy         = [[Miroljub Labus]]<br />[[Ivana Duli\u0107-Markovi\u0107]]<br />[[Bo\u017eidar \u0110eli\u0107]]\n|term_start     = 4 March 2004\n|term_end       = 7 July 2008\n|predecessor    = [[Zoran \u017divkovi\u0107 (politician)|Zoran \u017divkovi\u0107]]\n|successor      = [[Mirko Cvetkovi\u0107]]\n|office1        = 4th [[President of Serbia and Montenegro|President of Yugoslavia]]\n|primeminister1 = [[Momir Bulatovi\u0107]]<br />[[Zoran \u017di\u017ei\u0107]]<br />[[Dragi\u0161a Pe\u0161i\u0107]]\n|term_start1    = 7 October 2000\n|term_end1      = 7 March 2003\n|predecessor1   = [[Slobodan Milo\u0161evi\u0107]]\n|successor1     = [[Svetozar Marovi\u0107]]\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1944|3|24|df=y}}\n|birth_place    = [[Belgrade]], [[Territory of the Military Commander in Serbia|German-occupied Serbia]]\n|death_date     = \n|death_place    = \n|party          = [[Democratic Party (Serbia)|DS]] {{small|(1990\u20131992)}}<br />[[Democratic Party of Serbia|DSS]] {{small|(1992\u20132014)}}\n|spouse         = {{marriage|Zorica Radovi\u0107|1976|2015|end=her death}}\n|alma_mater     = [[University of Belgrade Faculty of Law|University of Belgrade]]\n|signature      = Signature of Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica.png\n}}\n\n'''Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica''' ({{lang-sr-cyrl|\u0412\u043e\u0458\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u041a\u043e\u0448\u0442\u0443\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430, {{IPA-sh|\u028b\u01d2jisla\u028b ko\u0283t\u01d4nit\u0361sa|pron|sr-Vojislav_Kostunica.ogg}}}}; born 24 March 1944) is a former [[Serbia]]n politician. He was the last [[President of Serbia and Montenegro|president of Yugoslavia]] from 2000 to 2003, and the [[Prime Minister of Serbia|prime minister of Serbia]] in two terms (from 2004 to 2007, and from 2007 to 2008).<ref name=kostunica>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/info/izbori2012/kandidati.php?yyyy=2012&mm=04&dd=20&nav_id=602358|title=Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica \u2013 kandidat DSS-a|publisher=B92|accessdate=15 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nKo\u0161tunica won the [[2000 Yugoslav general election|2000 Yugoslav presidential election]] as a candidate of a wide alliance [[Democratic Opposition of Serbia]] (DOS), which led to [[Overthrow of Slobodan Milo\u0161evi\u0107|overthrow]] of [[Slobodan Milo\u0161evi\u0107]] and withdrawal of [[Sanctions against Yugoslavia|international sanctions]] against [[Serbia and Montenegro|Yugoslavia]]. He strictly opposed the cooperation with [[International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia]] (ICTY) and his party left the coalition government in protest of a decision to extradite Slobodan Milo\u0161evi\u0107 to the ICTY. After the [[2003 Serbian parliamentary election]], the first elections after the dissolution of DOS and [[Assassination of Zoran \u0110in\u0111i\u0107|assassination]] of Prime Minister [[Zoran \u0110in\u0111i\u0107]], Ko\u0161tunica formed the [[minority government]] with the support of the Milo\u0161evi\u0107's [[Socialist Party of Serbia]] and became the head of government. He was one of the crucial figures for the adoption of the [[Constitution of Serbia|first constitution]] of an independent Serbia, as well as for declaring Serbia a [[neutral country]]. During his second government, he opposed signing the [[Stabilisation and Association Process|Stabilisation and Association Agreement]] (SAA), leading to the fall of the government after a year and early elections won by pro-European parties.\n\nHe was one of the founders and the first president of the [[Democratic Party of Serbia]] since its creation in 1992 until 19 March 2014, when he resigned as party president and retired from active politics after his party failed to reach 5% threshold to enter [[National Assembly (Serbia)|the Parliament]] on [[2014 Serbian parliamentary election|March 16 elections]] for the first time in its history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.balkaneu.com/kostunicas-resignation-political-retirement-serbian-euro-skeptic/|title=Kostunica`s resignation: Political retirement of last Serbian Euro-skeptic|publisher=balkaneu.com|date=20 March 2014|accessdate=3 May 2014}}</ref> In October 2014, he left the party after disagreements with new party leadership over what he saw as their abandonment of the policy of political neutrality.<ref name=vreme>{{cite web|url=http://www.vreme.co.rs/cms/view.php?id=1236037|title=Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica napustio DSS|publisher=[[Vreme]]|date=14 October 2014|accessdate=1 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, he was one of the founders of [[Statehood Movement of Serbia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dps.rs/Proglas/KompletanProglas.htm|title=Srbiji je potreban dr\u017eavotvorni pokret|publisher=dps.rs|date=14 November 2014|accessdate=1 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blic.rs/Vesti/Politika/567526/Slobodan-Samardzic-predsednik-Drzavotvornog-pokreta-Srbije|title=Slobodan Samard\u017ei\u0107 predsednik Dr\u017eavotvornog pokreta Srbije|publisher=[[Blic]]|date=13 June 2015|accessdate=1 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nKo\u0161tunica was born on 24 March 1944 in his family home in [[Belgrade]], Yugoslavia. As a youth he went by the nickname 'Voja'.<ref name=kostunica/> He was educated in Belgrade, where he finished elementary school, and graduated from the Second Belgrade High School in 1962. Ko\u0161tunica enrolled in the [[University of Belgrade]]'s [[University of Belgrade Faculty of Law|Faculty of Law]] the same year, graduating in 1966.<ref name=kostunica/> He earned his [[master's degree]] in 1970 and his [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in 1974 with his thesis ''\"Institutionalized Opposition in the Political System of Capitalism\"''.<ref name=kostunica/>\n\nKo\u0161tunica was an assistant at the faculty from 1970 until 1974, when he left due to a political purge at the university for criticising the [[Communism|communist]] regime of [[Josip Broz Tito]].<ref name=kostunica/> After his expulsion, Ko\u0161tunica worked at the Institute of Social Sciences, and from 1981 at the Institute for Philosophy and Social Theory, where he engaged in the protection of [[human rights]], specifically in the defence of [[freedom of thought]] and [[Freedom of speech|expression]].<ref name=kostunica/>\n\n==Political career==\nKo\u0161tunica was a founding member of the [[Democratic Party (Serbia)|Democratic Party]] (DS) in 1989.<ref name=kostunica/> He left the Democratic Party in 1992 over opposing views in leadership and formed the [[Democratic Party of Serbia]].<ref name=kostunica/>\n\n===President of Yugoslavia (2000\u201303)===\nSupported by both nationalists and liberals, the [[Democratic Opposition of Serbia]] backed him in the [[2000 Yugoslav general election|2000 presidential election]] against incumbent [[Slobodan Milo\u0161evi\u0107]]. Ko\u0161tunica received 50.26 percent of the vote in the first round of voting, just a few thousand votes over the threshold needed to win outright. Milo\u0161evi\u0107 disputed the results of the first round, claiming that Ko\u0161tunica had only received 49 percent of the vote and a runoff was required. The Otpor movement, a student-led movement to oust Milosevic and install free and fair elections, organized a protest where thousands of Serbians participated in strikes and took over the Belgrade capital and forced Milo\u0161evi\u0107 to accept the results and step down as president. Ko\u0161tunica then assumed the presidency. He was the last president of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia. Ko\u0161tunica opposed the extradition of his predecessor, to the Hague Tribunal, and voiced opposition to the court several times.\n\n===Prime Minister of Serbia (2004\u201308)===\n{{See also|First cabinet of Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica|Second cabinet of Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica}}\nFollowing the parliamentary elections in December 2003, in which the DSS emerged as the largest of the reformist parties, Ko\u0161tunica became prime minister in March 2004 at the head of the new minority government, albeit with the support of the [[Socialist Party of Serbia]]. However, as a result of the bad showing of the presidential candidate [[Dragan Mar\u0161i\u0107anin]] in the [[2004 Serbian presidential election|2004 presidential election]], Ko\u0161tunica announced that parliamentary elections should be expected by the end of the year just following the adoption of a new Constitution.\n\nOn 15 May 2007, after a brief crisis in his coalition, he was sworn in for his second term as prime minister.\n\n==Policy==\nKo\u0161tunica is a [[Conservatism|conservative]] politician with strong [[anti-communist]] views but also critical of the [[Western world|West]], namely the [[United States]] and the [[European Union]]. In an interview with German weekly news magazine [[Der Spiegel]], Ko\u0161tunica stated he is ''\"fairly close to [[Charles de Gaulle|de Gaulle]]\"'', in his views.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/spiegel/0,1518,102448,00.html|title=English Summaries|publisher=Der Spiegel|date=13 November 2000|accessdate=21 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n===On Kosovo===\n[[File:President Bush greets President Vojislav Kostunica of Yugoslavia..jpg|thumb|right|President [[George W. Bush]] greets Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica, then [[President of Yugoslavia]], in the [[White House]].]]\n[[File:Vladimir Putin with Vojislav Kostunica-1.jpg|thumb|right|With Ko\u0161tunica in [[the Kremlin]] on 27 oktober 2000.]]\n[[File:Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica and Condoleezza Rice.jpg|thumb|right|With [[Condoleezza Rice|Secretary Rice]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] on 12 July 2006.]]\nOn 21 February 2008, following Kosovo's declaration of independence, Ko\u0161tunica made an emotional speech in Belgrade, which included the following: {{quote|Dear citizens of Serbia, Serbia! What is Kosovo? Where is Kosovo? Whose is Kosovo? Is there anyone among us who is not from Kosovo? Is there anyone among us who thinks that Kosovo does not belong to us? Kosovo&nbsp;\u2013 that's Serbia's first name. Kosovo belongs to Serbia. Kosovo belongs to the Serbian people. That\u2019s how it has been for ever. That's how it's going to be for ever. There is no force, no threat, and no punishment big and hideous enough for any Serb, at any time, to say anything different but, Kosovo is Serbia! Never will anyone hear from us that the Patriarchate of Pe\u0107 does not belong to us, that Visoki De\u010dani and Gra\u010danica are not ours! That the place where we were born is not ours; we and our state and our church and everything that makes us what we are today! If we as Serbs renounce Serbianhood, our origin, our Kosovo, our ancestors and our history&nbsp;\u2013 then, who are we Serbs? What is our name then?<ref>{{cite web|title=The Promise is Given, Kosovo is Serbia as Long as We Live|date=21 February 2008|work=[[Tanjug]], via Serbian Orthodox Church|url=http://www.spc.rs/eng/promise_given_kosovo_serbia_long_we_live}}</ref>}}\nBuses took thousands of supporters to the rally; some protestors then attacked embassies and looted shops.<ref>{{cite book|last=Judah|title=The Serbs|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=978-0-300-15826-7|page=359}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 February 2008, Ko\u0161tunica demanded that the United States rescind its recognition of [[Kosovo]], warning that \"there will be no stability until the fake state\" is annulled.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/02/25/AR2008022502484.html|title=Putin's Likely Successor, Pledging Support for Serbia, Signs Pipeline Deal|agency=Associated Press|work=The Washington Post|first=Danica|last=Kirka|date=26 February 2008|page=A11}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 March 2008, Ko\u0161tunica, as Prime Minister of Serbia, called for new elections on 11 May after the collapse of his party's coalition with the [[Democratic Party (Serbia)|Democratic Party]] over relations with the [[European Union]] and [[2008 Kosovo declaration of independence|Kosovo's unilateral declaration of independence]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/7285322.stm|title=Serbia's ruling coalition collapses|publisher=BBC|date=8 March 2008}}</ref>\n\n===On the European Union===\nOn 4 April 2008, Ko\u0161tunica stated that [[European Union|EU]] membership was no longer on the agenda for Serbia. He stated that before EU integration could continue, Serbia and the EU must discuss the matter of Serbia\u2019s territorial integrity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=04&dd=04&nav_id=49087|title=Ko\u0161tunica: EU membership not on agenda|publisher=B92|date=4 April 2008|accessdate=21 December 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607014646/http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=04&dd=04&nav_id=49087|archivedate=7 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nHe stated that Serbia must not by any means sign the [[Stabilisation and Association Process|Stabilisation and Association Agreement]], which he referred to the agreement as ''\u00ab[[Javier Solana|Solana]]'s agreement\u00bb''.<ref>[http://www.mtsmondo.com/news/world/text.php?vest=93149 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080412053332/http://www.mtsmondo.com/news/world/text.php?vest=93149 |date=12 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\nOn 21 April 2008 Ko\u0161tunica said that the SAA was in the interests of [[Olli Rehn]] and [[Javier Solana]] and not in Serbia's national interests. He also said that \"the [[NATO]] pact cannot claim that Serbia recognised [[Kosovo]]\u2019s independence with that signature.\" and that \"the only thing the NATO pact will be able to claim is that individual parties signed Solana\u2019s agreement.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=04&dd=21&nav_id=49620|title=SAA not in Serbia's state interests|publisher=B92|date=21 April 2008|accessdate=21 December 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607015423/http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=04&dd=21&nav_id=49620|archivedate=7 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 April 2008 he said that anyone who signed the SAA on behalf of Serbia would become an accomplice to tearing Serbia apart. He also implied there is a cover-up of something in the agreement by saying: \"I am convinced every Serbian sees that things are being covered up, and that there is something seriously amiss with the Solana agreement.\" and he asked \"who in Serbia dares to ignore these facts and conceal the real goal of Solana's agreement.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=04&dd=26&nav_id=49765|title=Ko\u0161tunica on SAA: Who dares to become accomplice|publisher=B92|date=26 April 2008|accessdate=21 December 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607020726/http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=04&dd=26&nav_id=49765|archive-date=7 June 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 April 2008 he said that \"the signature will not be valid for Serbia and whoever signs the SAA will have to assume responsibility for such an act\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=04&dd=28&nav_id=49818|title=Ko\u0161tunica slams EU deal signing as anti-state|publisher=B92|date=28 April 2008|accessdate=21 December 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607020659/http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=04&dd=28&nav_id=49818|archive-date=7 June 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 May 2008 Ko\u0161tunica said that Russian Foreign Minister [[Sergey Lavrov]] was right when he said that the SAA should have been signed before Kosovo's unilateral declaration of independence and its recognition by 18 EU member states at the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=05&dd=01&nav_id=49898|title=Ko\u0161tunica agrees with Lavrov: SAA long overdue|publisher=B92|date=1 May 2008|accessdate=21 December 2010}}</ref> One day later on 2 May 2008 he vowed to annul the agreement after the election, calling it \"a trick\", \"[[Javier Solana|Solana]]'s agreement\" and \"the [[Boris Tadi\u0107|Tadi\u0107]]-[[Bo\u017eidar \u0110eli\u0107|\u0110eli\u0107]] SAA signature\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=05&dd=02&nav_id=49912|title=EU deal signature will be annulled|publisher=B92|date=2 May 2008|accessdate=21 December 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080503193600/http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=05&dd=02&nav_id=49912|archivedate=3 May 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He said he refers to the act of signing of the SAA as anti-Constitutional and anti-state that leads to the breakup of Serbia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=05&dd=03&nav_id=49931|title=Ko\u0161tunica: SAA breaking Serbia up|publisher=B92|date=3 May 2008|accessdate=21 December 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607020416/http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=05&dd=03&nav_id=49931|archive-date=7 June 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A spokesperson of Ko\u0161tunica's Democratic Party of Serbia stated that Tadi\u0107 was putting a seal of [[Judas Iscariot|Judas]] of his party coalition to the Solana Agreement by signing it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=04&dd=29&nav_id=49830|title=DSS: EU deal signature, seal of Judas|publisher=B92|date=29 April 2008|accessdate=21 December 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607020551/http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=04&dd=29&nav_id=49830|archive-date=7 June 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 4 May he called the document \"a forgery and a trick\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=05&dd=04&nav_id=49951|title=Ko\u0161tunica says signed EU deal is forgery|publisher=B92|date=4 May 2008|accessdate=21 December 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607015807/http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=05&dd=04&nav_id=49951|archive-date=7 June 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Democratic Party of Serbia]]\n*[[Cabinet of Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica]] (2004\u20132007)\n*[[Cabinet of Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica II]] (2007\u20132008)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica}}\n*[http://www.dps.rs/ Statehood Movement of Serbia] - Official website\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Slobodan Milo\u0161evi\u0107]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of Serbia and Montenegro|President of Yugoslavia]]|years=2000\u20132003}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Svetozar Marovi\u0107]]<br />{{nowrap|''{{small|as [[President of Serbia and Montenegro]]}}''}}}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Zoran \u017divkovi\u0107 (politician)|Zoran \u017divkovi\u0107]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Serbia]]|years=2004\u20132008}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mirko Cvetkovi\u0107]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=Post established}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Leader of the [[Democratic Party of Serbia]]|years=1992\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Aleksandar Popovi\u0107 (politician)|Aleksandar Popovi\u0107]]<br />(Acting)}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Cabinet of Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica I}}\n{{Cabinet of Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica II}}\n{{SerbianPM}}\n{{President of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kostunica, Vojislav}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party (Serbia) politicians]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party of Serbia politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Belgrade]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Serbia and Montenegro]]\n[[Category:Candidates for President of Serbia]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Serbia]]\n[[Category:Serbian anti-communists]]\n[[Category:Serbian democracy activists]]\n[[Category:Serbian nationalists]]\n[[Category:Serbian political scientists]]\n[[Category:University of Belgrade faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Belgrade Faculty of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav dissidents]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name           = Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica\n|image          = Flickr - europeanpeoplesparty - EPP Congress Rome 2006 (68)-Cropped.jpg\n|honorific_prefix = [[Doctor of law|Dr. iur.]]\n|caption        = Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica during the 2006 European People's Party Congress in Rome, Italy\n|office         = [[List of Prime Ministers of Serbia|8th]] [[Prime Minister of Serbia]]\n|president      = [[Dragan Mar\u0161i\u0107anin]] {{small|(acting)}}<br />[[Vojislav Mihailovi\u0107]] {{small|(acting)}}<br />[[Predrag Markovi\u0107]] {{small|(acting)}}<br />[[Boris Tadi\u0107]]\n|deputy         = [[Miroljub Labus]]<br />[[Ivana Duli\u0107-Markovi\u0107]]<br />[[Bo\u017eidar \u0110eli\u0107]]\n|term_start     = 4 March 2004\n|term_end       = 7 July 2008\n|predecessor    = [[Zoran \u017divkovi\u0107 (politician)|Zoran \u017divkovi\u0107]]\n|successor      = [[Mirko Cvetkovi\u0107]]\n|office1        = 4th [[President of Serbia and Montenegro|President of Yugoslavia]]\n|primeminister1 = [[Momir Bulatovi\u0107]]<br />[[Zoran \u017di\u017ei\u0107]]<br />[[Dragi\u0161a Pe\u0161i\u0107]]\n|term_start1    = 7 October 2000\n|term_end1      = 7 March 2003\n|predecessor1   = [[Slobodan Milo\u0161evi\u0107]]\n|successor1     = [[Svetozar Marovi\u0107]]\n|birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1944|3|24|df=y}}\n|birth_place    = [[Belgrade]], [[Territory of the Military Commander in Serbia|German-occupied Serbia]]\n|death_date     = \n|death_place    = \n|party          = [[Democratic Party (Serbia)|DS]] {{small|(1990\u20131992)}}<br />[[Democratic Party of Serbia|DSS]] {{small|(1992\u20132014)}}\n|spouse         = {{marriage|Zorica Radovi\u0107|1976|2015|end=her death}}\n|alma_mater     = [[University of Belgrade Faculty of Law|University of Belgrade]]\n|signature      = Signature of Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica.png\n}}\n\n'''Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica''' ({{lang-sr-cyrl|\u0412\u043e\u0458\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432 \u041a\u043e\u0448\u0442\u0443\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430, {{IPA-sh|\u028b\u01d2jisla\u028b ko\u0283t\u01d4nit\u0361sa|pron|sr-Vojislav_Kostunica.ogg}}}}; born 24 March 1944) is a former [[Serbia]]n politician. He was the last [[President of Serbia and Montenegro|president of Yugoslavia]] from 2000 to 2003, and the [[Prime Minister of Serbia|prime minister of Serbia]] in two terms (from 2004 to 2007, and from 2007 to 2008).<ref name=kostunica>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/info/izbori2012/kandidati.php?yyyy=2012&mm=04&dd=20&nav_id=602358|title=Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica \u2013 kandidat DSS-a|publisher=B92|accessdate=15 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nKo\u0161tunica won the [[2000 Yugoslav general election|2000 Yugoslav presidential election]] as a candidate of a wide alliance [[Democratic Opposition of Serbia]] (DOS), which led to [[Overthrow of Slobodan Milo\u0161evi\u0107|overthrow]] of [[Slobodan Milo\u0161evi\u0107]] and withdrawal of [[Sanctions against Yugoslavia|international sanctions]] against [[Serbia and Montenegro|Yugoslavia]]. He strictly opposed the cooperation with [[International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia]] (ICTY) and his party left the coalition government in protest of a decision to extradite Slobodan Milo\u0161evi\u0107 to the ICTY. After the [[2003 Serbian parliamentary election]], the first elections after the dissolution of DOS and [[Assassination of Zoran \u0110in\u0111i\u0107|assassination]] of Prime Minister [[Zoran \u0110in\u0111i\u0107]], Ko\u0161tunica formed the [[minority government]] with the support of the Milo\u0161evi\u0107's [[Socialist Party of Serbia]] and became the head of government. He was one of the crucial figures for the adoption of the [[Constitution of Serbia|first constitution]] of an independent Serbia, as well as for declaring Serbia a [[neutral country]]. During his second government, he opposed signing the [[Stabilisation and Association Process|Stabilisation and Association Agreement]] (SAA), leading to the fall of the government after a year and early elections won by pro-European parties.\n\nHe was one of the founders and the first president of the [[Democratic Party of Serbia]] since its creation in 1992 until 19 March 2014, when he resigned as party president and retired from active politics after his party failed to reach 5% threshold to enter [[National Assembly (Serbia)|the Parliament]] on [[2014 Serbian parliamentary election|March 16 elections]] for the first time in its history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.balkaneu.com/kostunicas-resignation-political-retirement-serbian-euro-skeptic/|title=Kostunica`s resignation: Political retirement of last Serbian Euro-skeptic|publisher=balkaneu.com|date=20 March 2014|accessdate=3 May 2014}}</ref> In October 2014, he left the party after disagreements with new party leadership over what he saw as their abandonment of the policy of political neutrality.<ref name=vreme>{{cite web|url=http://www.vreme.co.rs/cms/view.php?id=1236037|title=Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica napustio DSS|publisher=[[Vreme]]|date=14 October 2014|accessdate=1 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, he was one of the founders of [[Statehood Movement of Serbia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dps.rs/Proglas/KompletanProglas.htm|title=Srbiji je potreban dr\u017eavotvorni pokret|publisher=dps.rs|date=14 November 2014|accessdate=1 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blic.rs/Vesti/Politika/567526/Slobodan-Samardzic-predsednik-Drzavotvornog-pokreta-Srbije|title=Slobodan Samard\u017ei\u0107 predsednik Dr\u017eavotvornog pokreta Srbije|publisher=[[Blic]]|date=13 June 2015|accessdate=1 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nKo\u0161tunica was born on 24 March 1944 in his family home in [[Belgrade]], Yugoslavia. As a youth he went by the nickname 'Voja'.<ref name=kostunica/> He was educated in Belgrade, where he finished elementary school, and graduated from the Second Belgrade High School in 1962. Ko\u0161tunica enrolled in the [[University of Belgrade]]'s [[University of Belgrade Faculty of Law|Faculty of Law]] the same year, graduating in 1966.<ref name=kostunica/> He earned his [[master's degree]] in 1970 and his [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in 1974 with his thesis ''\"Institutionalized Opposition in the Political System of Capitalism\"''.<ref name=kostunica/>\n\nKo\u0161tunica was an assistant at the faculty from 1970 until 1974, when he left due to a political purge at the university for criticising the [[Communism|communist]] regime of [[Josip Broz Tito]].<ref name=kostunica/> After his expulsion, Ko\u0161tunica worked at the Institute of Social Sciences, and from 1981 at the Institute for Philosophy and Social Theory, where he engaged in the protection of [[human rights]], specifically in the defence of [[freedom of thought]] and [[Freedom of speech|expression]].<ref name=kostunica/>\n\n==Political career==\nKo\u0161tunica was a founding member of the [[Democratic Party (Serbia)|Democratic Party]] (DS) in 1989.<ref name=kostunica/> He left the Democratic Party in 1992 over opposing views in leadership and formed the [[Democratic Party of Serbia]].<ref name=kostunica/>\n\n===President of Yugoslavia (2000\u201303)===\nSupported by both nationalists and liberals, the [[Democratic Opposition of Serbia]] backed him in the [[2000 Yugoslav general election|2000 presidential election]] against incumbent [[Slobodan Milo\u0161evi\u0107]]. Ko\u0161tunica received 50.26 percent of the vote in the first round of voting, just a few thousand votes over the threshold needed to win outright. Milo\u0161evi\u0107 disputed the results of the first round, claiming that Ko\u0161tunica had only received 49 percent of the vote and a runoff was required. The Otpor movement, a student-led movement to oust Milosevic and install free and fair elections, organized a protest where thousands of Serbians participated in strikes and took over the Belgrade capital and forced Milo\u0161evi\u0107 to accept the results and step down as president. Ko\u0161tunica then assumed the presidency. He was the last president of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia. Ko\u0161tunica opposed the extradition of his predecessor, to the Hague Tribunal, and voiced opposition to the court several times.\n\n===Prime Minister of Serbia (2004\u201308)===\n{{See also|First cabinet of Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica|Second cabinet of Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica}}\nFollowing the parliamentary elections in December 2003, in which the DSS emerged as the largest of the reformist parties, Ko\u0161tunica became prime minister in March 2004 at the head of the new minority government, albeit with the support of the [[Socialist Party of Serbia]]. However, as a result of the bad showing of the presidential candidate [[Dragan Mar\u0161i\u0107anin]] in the [[2004 Serbian presidential election|2004 presidential election]], Ko\u0161tunica announced that parliamentary elections should be expected by the end of the year just following the adoption of a new Constitution.\n\nOn 15 May 2007, after a brief crisis in his coalition, he was sworn in for his second term as prime minister.\n\n==Policy==\nKo\u0161tunica is a [[Conservatism|conservative]] politician with strong [[anti-communist]] views but also critical of the [[Western world|West]], namely the [[United States]] and the [[European Union]]. In an interview with German weekly news magazine [[Der Spiegel]], Ko\u0161tunica stated he is ''\"fairly close to [[Charles de Gaulle|de Gaulle]]\"'', in his views.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/spiegel/0,1518,102448,00.html|title=English Summaries|publisher=Der Spiegel|date=13 November 2000|accessdate=21 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n===On Kosovo===\n[[File:President Bush greets President Vojislav Kostunica of Yugoslavia..jpg|thumb|right|President [[George W. Bush]] greets Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica, then [[President of Yugoslavia]], in the [[White House]].]]\n[[File:Vladimir Putin with Vojislav Kostunica-1.jpg|thumb|right|With Ko\u0161tunica in [[the Kremlin]] on 27 oktober 2000.]]\n[[File:Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica and Condoleezza Rice.jpg|thumb|right|With [[Condoleezza Rice|Secretary Rice]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] on 12 July 2006.]]\nOn 21 February 2008, following Kosovo's declaration of independence, Ko\u0161tunica made an emotional speech in Belgrade, which included the following: {{quote|Dear citizens of Serbia, Serbia! What is Kosovo? Where is Kosovo? Whose is Kosovo? Is there anyone among us who is not from Kosovo? Is there anyone among us who thinks that Kosovo does not belong to us? Kosovo&nbsp;\u2013 that's Serbia's first name. Kosovo belongs to Serbia. Kosovo belongs to the Serbian people. That\u2019s how it has been for ever. That's how it's going to be for ever. There is no force, no threat, and no punishment big and hideous enough for any Serb, at any time, to say anything different but, Kosovo is Serbia! Never will anyone hear from us that the Patriarchate of Pe\u0107 does not belong to us, that Visoki De\u010dani and Gra\u010danica are not ours! That the place where we were born is not ours; we and our state and our church and everything that makes us what we are today! If we as Serbs renounce Serbianhood, our origin, our Kosovo, our ancestors and our history&nbsp;\u2013 then, who are we Serbs? What is our name then?<ref>{{cite web|title=The Promise is Given, Kosovo is Serbia as Long as We Live|date=21 February 2008|work=[[Tanjug]], via Serbian Orthodox Church|url=http://www.spc.rs/eng/promise_given_kosovo_serbia_long_we_live}}</ref>}}\nBuses took thousands of supporters to the rally; some protestors then attacked embassies and looted shops.<ref>{{cite book|last=Judah|title=The Serbs|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=978-0-300-15826-7|page=359}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 February 2008, Ko\u0161tunica demanded that the United States rescind its recognition of [[Kosovo]], warning that \"there will be no stability until the fake state\" is annulled.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/02/25/AR2008022502484.html|title=Putin's Likely Successor, Pledging Support for Serbia, Signs Pipeline Deal|agency=Associated Press|work=The Washington Post|first=Danica|last=Kirka|date=26 February 2008|page=A11}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 March 2008, Ko\u0161tunica, as Prime Minister of Serbia, called for new elections on 11 May after the collapse of his party's coalition with the [[Democratic Party (Serbia)|Democratic Party]] over relations with the [[European Union]] and [[2008 Kosovo declaration of independence|Kosovo's unilateral declaration of independence]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/7285322.stm|title=Serbia's ruling coalition collapses|publisher=BBC|date=8 March 2008}}</ref>\n\n===On the European Union===\nOn 4 April 2008, Ko\u0161tunica stated that [[European Union|EU]] membership was no longer on the agenda for Serbia. He stated that before EU integration could continue, Serbia and the EU must discuss the matter of Serbia\u2019s territorial integrity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=04&dd=04&nav_id=49087|title=Ko\u0161tunica: EU membership not on agenda|publisher=B92|date=4 April 2008|accessdate=21 December 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607014646/http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=04&dd=04&nav_id=49087|archivedate=7 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nHe stated that Serbia must not by any means sign the [[Stabilisation and Association Process|Stabilisation and Association Agreement]], which he referred to the agreement as ''\u00ab[[Javier Solana|Solana]]'s agreement\u00bb''.<ref>[http://www.mtsmondo.com/news/world/text.php?vest=93149 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080412053332/http://www.mtsmondo.com/news/world/text.php?vest=93149 |date=12 April 2008 }}</ref>\n\nOn 21 April 2008 Ko\u0161tunica said that the SAA was in the interests of [[Olli Rehn]] and [[Javier Solana]] and not in Serbia's national interests. He also said that \"the [[NATO]] pact cannot claim that Serbia recognised [[Kosovo]]\u2019s independence with that signature.\" and that \"the only thing the NATO pact will be able to claim is that individual parties signed Solana\u2019s agreement.\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=04&dd=21&nav_id=49620|title=SAA not in Serbia's state interests|publisher=B92|date=21 April 2008|accessdate=21 December 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607015423/http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=04&dd=21&nav_id=49620|archivedate=7 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 April 2008 he said that anyone who signed the SAA on behalf of Serbia would become an accomplice to tearing Serbia apart. He also implied there is a cover-up of something in the agreement by saying: \"I am convinced every Serbian sees that things are being covered up, and that there is something seriously amiss with the Solana agreement.\" and he asked \"who in Serbia dares to ignore these facts and conceal the real goal of Solana's agreement.\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=04&dd=26&nav_id=49765|title=Ko\u0161tunica on SAA: Who dares to become accomplice|publisher=B92|date=26 April 2008|accessdate=21 December 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607020726/http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=04&dd=26&nav_id=49765|archive-date=7 June 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 April 2008 he said that \"the signature will not be valid for Serbia and whoever signs the SAA will have to assume responsibility for such an act\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=04&dd=28&nav_id=49818|title=Ko\u0161tunica slams EU deal signing as anti-state|publisher=B92|date=28 April 2008|accessdate=21 December 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607020659/http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=04&dd=28&nav_id=49818|archive-date=7 June 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 May 2008 Ko\u0161tunica said that Russian Foreign Minister [[Sergey Lavrov]] was right when he said that the SAA should have been signed before Kosovo's unilateral declaration of independence and its recognition by 18 EU member states at the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=05&dd=01&nav_id=49898|title=Ko\u0161tunica agrees with Lavrov: SAA long overdue|publisher=B92|date=1 May 2008|accessdate=21 December 2010}}</ref> One day later on 2 May 2008 he vowed to annul the agreement after the election, calling it \"a trick\", \"[[Javier Solana|Solana]]'s agreement\" and \"the [[Boris Tadi\u0107|Tadi\u0107]]-[[Bo\u017eidar \u0110eli\u0107|\u0110eli\u0107]] SAA signature\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=05&dd=02&nav_id=49912|title=EU deal signature will be annulled|publisher=B92|date=2 May 2008|accessdate=21 December 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080503193600/http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=05&dd=02&nav_id=49912|archivedate=3 May 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> He said he refers to the act of signing of the SAA as anti-Constitutional and anti-state that leads to the breakup of Serbia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=05&dd=03&nav_id=49931|title=Ko\u0161tunica: SAA breaking Serbia up|publisher=B92|date=3 May 2008|accessdate=21 December 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607020416/http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=05&dd=03&nav_id=49931|archive-date=7 June 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> A spokesperson of Ko\u0161tunica's Democratic Party of Serbia stated that Tadi\u0107 was putting a seal of [[Judas Iscariot|Judas]] of his party coalition to the Solana Agreement by signing it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=04&dd=29&nav_id=49830|title=DSS: EU deal signature, seal of Judas|publisher=B92|date=29 April 2008|accessdate=21 December 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607020551/http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=04&dd=29&nav_id=49830|archive-date=7 June 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> On 4 May he called the document \"a forgery and a trick\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=05&dd=04&nav_id=49951|title=Ko\u0161tunica says signed EU deal is forgery|publisher=B92|date=4 May 2008|accessdate=21 December 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607015807/http://www.b92.net/eng/news/politics-article.php?yyyy=2008&mm=05&dd=04&nav_id=49951|archive-date=7 June 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Democratic Party of Serbia]]\n*[[Cabinet of Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica]] (2004\u20132007)\n*[[Cabinet of Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica II]] (2007\u20132008)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica}}\n*[http://www.dps.rs/ Statehood Movement of Serbia] - Official website\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Slobodan Milo\u0161evi\u0107]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of Serbia and Montenegro|President of Yugoslavia]]|years=2000\u20132003}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Svetozar Marovi\u0107]]<br />{{nowrap|''{{small|as [[President of Serbia and Montenegro]]}}''}}}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Zoran \u017divkovi\u0107 (politician)|Zoran \u017divkovi\u0107]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of Serbia]]|years=2004\u20132008}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mirko Cvetkovi\u0107]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=Post established}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Leader of the [[Democratic Party of Serbia]]|years=1992\u20132014}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Aleksandar Popovi\u0107 (politician)|Aleksandar Popovi\u0107]]<br />(Acting)}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Cabinet of Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica I}}\n{{Cabinet of Vojislav Ko\u0161tunica II}}\n{{SerbianPM}}\n{{President of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kostunica, Vojislav}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party (Serbia) politicians]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party of Serbia politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Belgrade]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Serbia and Montenegro]]\n[[Category:Candidates for President of Serbia]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of Serbia]]\n[[Category:Serbian anti-communists]]\n[[Category:Serbian democracy activists]]\n[[Category:Serbian nationalists]]\n[[Category:Serbian political scientists]]\n[[Category:University of Belgrade faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Belgrade Faculty of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav dissidents]]\n", "name_user": "Illegitimate Barrister", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOn the European Union", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vojislav_Ko%C5%A1tunica"}
